aa(lp130
VNow, I'm not against glass.
p131
aVIt's an ancient and versatile material.
p132
aVIt's easy to manufacture and transport
p133
aVand install and replace
p134
aVand clean.
p135
aVIt comes in everything from enormous, ultraclear sheets
p136
aVto translucent bricks.
p137
aVNew coatings make it change mood
p138
aVin the shifting light.
p139
aVIn expensive cities like New York, it has the magical power
p140
aVof being able to multiply real estate values by allowing views,
p141
aVwhich is really the only commodity that developers have to offer
p142
aVto justify those surreal prices.
p143
aa(lp144
VIn the middle of the 19th century,
p145
aVwith the construction of the Crystal Palace in London,
p146
aVglass leapt to the top of the list of quintessentially modern substances.
p147
aVBy the mid-20th century,
p148
aVit had come to dominate the downtowns of some American cities,
p149
aVlargely through some really spectacular office buildings
p150
aVlike Lever House in midtown Manhattan, designed by Skidmore, Owings and Merrill.
p151
aVEventually, the technology advanced to the point
p152
aVwhere architects could design structures so transparent
p153
aVthey practically disappear.
p154
aVAnd along the way,
p155
aVglass became the default material of the high-rise city,
p156
aVand there's a very powerful reason for that.
p157
aVBecause as the world's populations converge on cities,
p158
aVthe least fortunate pack into jerry-built shantytowns.
p159
aVBut hundreds of millions of people need apartments and places to work
p160
aVin ever-larger buildings,
p161
aVso it makes economic sense to put up towers
p162
aVand wrap them in cheap and practical curtain walls.
p163
aa(lp164
VBut glass has a limited ability
p165
aVto be expressive.
